<section>
    <h2>1. Introduction</h2>
    <p>
        Description of Data is a branch of statistics that deals with the collection,
        organization, presentation, and analysis of data.
    </p>
</section>

<section>
    <h2>2. Data</h2>
    <p>
        Data refers to a collection of facts, figures, or observations collected for analysis.
    </p>
</section>

<!-- TARGET SECTION WITH ID -->
<section id="types-of-variables">
    <h2>3. Types of Variables</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><b>Qualitative Variables:</b> Non-numerical data such as gender, color, or type.</li>
        <li><b>Quantitative Variables:</b> Numerical data such as height, weight, and marks.</li>
        <li><b>Discrete Variables:</b> Countable values (e.g., number of students).</li>
        <li><b>Continuous Variables:</b> Measurable values (e.g., time, temperature).</li>
    </ul>
</section>

<section>
    <h2>4. Mean</h2>
    <p>Mean is the arithmetic average of a set of values.</p>
    <p><b>Formula:</b> Mean = (Sum of observations) / (Number of observations)</p>
</section>

<section>
    <h2>5. Weighted Mean</h2>
    <p>
        Weighted mean is an average where each value has a specific weight.
    </p>
    <p><b>Formula:</b> Weighted Mean = Σ(wx) / Σw</p>
</section>

<section>
    <h2>6. Median</h2>
    <p>
        Median is the middle value when data is arranged in order.
    </p>
</section>

<section>
    <h2>7. Mode</h2>
    <p>
        Mode is the value that occurs most frequently.
    </p>
</section>

<section>
    <h2>8. Quartiles</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><b>Q1:</b> First quartile (25%)</li>
        <li><b>Q2:</b> Median</li>
        <li><b>Q3:</b> Third quartile (75%)</li>
    </ul>
</section>

<section>
    <h2>9. Variance</h2>
    <p><b>Formula:</b> Variance = Σ(x − x̄)² / n</p>
</section>

<section>
    <h2>10. Coefficient of Variation</h2>
    <p><b>Formula:</b> CV = (Standard Deviation / Mean) × 100</p>
</section>

<section>
    <h2>11. Skewness</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>Positive Skewness</li>
        <li>Negative Skewness</li>
        <li>Zero Skewness</li>
    </ul>
</section>

<section>
    <h2>12. Histogram</h2>
    <p>Histogram shows frequency using bars.</p>
</section>

<section>
    <h2>13. Box Plot</h2>
    <p>Box plot represents five-number summary.</p>
</section>

<section>
    <h2>Conclusion</h2>
    <p>Description of data helps in better understanding and decision-making.</p>
</section>

